#! /usr/bin/env zerg
#
# Specifications
#
# The `spec` keyword defines a contract that types can implement. The functions can accept any type that follow the
# contract can call the functions defined in the spec. The spec is a powerful tool for defining interfaces and ensuring
# that types adhere to a specific set of behaviors.
#
# It allows for polymorphism and code reuse, any function that accepts a instance of a spec is search by the following order:
#
#   1. The function implementation in the type itself for the spec.
#   2. The default implementation defined in the spec, if there is any.
#   3. Raise the `NotImplemented` error.

# The `spec` keyword defines a specification, which is a contract that types can implement. Any type that implements a
# spec must provide explicit implementations the spec's functions, the missing implementation will be considered as
# `NotImplemented` and will raise an error if called. It is the syntax sugar for defining a large spec but only focus
# on a few functions, and reduce the redundant non-implemented functions.
#
# For example, there is a struct `Point`. Without `impl Point for Printable {}`, the `Point` instance cannot be considered
# as a `Printable` type, and Zerg will raise an compile-time error if you try to pass it to a function that required.
#
# Without well-implemented specs, like only implement the spec but not implement the required functions, the Zerg can
# compile the code successfully, and treat the type as a `Printable` type, but it will raise a runtime error if you try
# to call the function defined in the spec.
spec Printable {
	fn to_string() -> str
}

# You can define the spec with the generic type parameter, and the function can also use the generic type parameter.
# The Iterator spec defines a contract for types that can be iterated over, and the `next` function is expected to return
# the next value in the iteration, or `nil` if there are no more values to iterate over.
#
# Any type that implements `Iterator[T]` can be used directly in a `for n in m` loop. Built-in types like ranges and
# channels implement this spec automatically, so `for i in 0..5` and `for v in ch` work out of the box.
spec Iterator[T] {
	fn next() -> T?
}


# The `spec` also can define the default implementation for the functions, for the functions that are not implemented by the
# type, it will use the default implementation.
spec Hashable {
	fn hash() -> int {
		return 0
	}
}

# Specs are flat: one spec cannot extend or require another spec (there is no `spec Ord: Eq { ... }` form). If a function
# needs a type that satisfies more than one spec, it expresses that at the call site with a multi-bound generic â€” for
# example `fn sort[T: Eq + Ord](items: list[T])` â€” rather than baking the relationship into the spec definitions. This
# keeps each spec self-contained and free of hidden coupling, at the cost of callers spelling out every spec they rely on.

# The empty structure `Demo` is defined, and it implements the `Printable` spec. This means that any instance of `Demo` can be
# treated as a `Printable` type.
#
# Each `impl Type for Spec` block names exactly one spec. A type that needs to satisfy multiple specs must write one separate
# `impl` block per spec â€” there is no combined `impl Type for Spec1, Spec2 { ... }` form. This keeps each block self-contained
# and makes it unambiguous which method belongs to which spec, at the cost of a little extra boilerplate.
struct Demo {}

impl Demo for Printable {
	fn to_string() -> str {
		return "This is a demo struct."
	}
}

# The function `display` is a generic function that takes a type parameter `T` constrained by the `Printable` spec. This means
# that any type `T` passed to the `display` function must follow the contract defined by the `Printable` spec.
fn display[T: Printable](item: T) {
	print item.to_string()
}

# The `Default` struct implements `Hashable` without providing the `hash` method. Because `Hashable` defines a default
# implementation for `hash`, the missing method is considered implemented by the default, and calling `hash()` on a `Default`
# instance is safe â€” it returns 0, the value from the default implementation.
struct Default {}

impl Default for Hashable {}

# The `Counter` struct implements `Hashable` and provides its own `hash` method, which overrides the default implementation.
# When `hash()` is called on a `Counter` instance, the overridden implementation is used instead of the default one. The
# resolution order â€” type's own impl, then spec default, then `NotImplemented` â€” is applied per-method, so a single impl
# block can mix overridden and inherited methods freely.
struct Counter {
	count: int
}

impl Counter for Hashable {
	fn hash() -> int {
		return this.count
	}
}

print Default {}.hash()           # 0  â€” inherited from the spec default
print Counter { count: 42 }.hash()  # 42 â€” overridden by the type's own impl

# Multi-bound generic. A type parameter can be constrained by more than one spec using `+` as the separator, which reads
# as "all of these specs must be satisfied". Because specs are flat (no inheritance), this is the only way to express a
# combined requirement. Here `show` accepts any `T` that is both `Printable` and `Hashable`, and can therefore call
# methods from either spec on the same value. `Counter` already impls `Hashable` above; an additional `impl` block makes
# it `Printable` too, and each spec has its own block (see the "one spec per impl block" rule earlier).
impl Counter for Printable {
	fn to_string() -> str {
		return "Counter({this.count})"
	}
}

fn show[T: Printable + Hashable](x: T) {
	print x.to_string()
	print x.hash()
}

show(Counter { count: 7 })  # prints "Counter(7)" then 7

# A spec can also be used directly as a type, not only as a generic bound. Writing `list[Printable]`, `item: Printable`,
# or `fn f(x: Printable)` means "any concrete type that implements Printable", with the actual type resolved at runtime.
# The compiler picks the dispatch strategy from context:
#
#   - Spec used as a bound (`fn f[T: Printable](x: T)`): monomorphized to the concrete `T` at each call site. No runtime
#     lookup, no per-element type tag â€” the usual zero-cost generic.
#   - Spec used as a type (`fn f(x: Printable)`, `list[Printable]`): dispatched at runtime via a vtable. Each value
#     carries enough information for the runtime to find the correct method implementation.
#
# The second form lets a single collection hold values whose concrete types differ, as long as every value satisfies the
# spec. Below, `items` mixes `Counter` and `Demo` â€” both implement `Printable`, but they are otherwise unrelated types.
items: list[Printable] = [Counter { count: 1 }, Counter { count: 2 }, Demo {}]

for item in items {
	print item.to_string()  # dispatched at runtime â€” each element may be a different concrete type
}

# Finale: a deliberate runtime panic. The `Broken` struct implements `Printable` but provides no `to_string` method. The
# compiler still treats `Broken` as `Printable` and compiles successfully, so the missing method only surfaces when it is
# actually invoked â€” at which point the `NotImplemented` stub panics the current task. Placed last on purpose: every demo
# above (default-impl inheritance, override, multi-bound generic, runtime polymorphism via `list[Printable]`) runs cleanly
# before this line crashes the program.
struct Broken {}

impl Broken for Printable {}

display(Broken {})  # runtime error: NotImplemented â€” program ends here
